## Broadcast vs Postgres Changes — Architecture Decision

```
Use BROADCAST when:
  ✅ High-frequency updates (cursor, typing indicator, game state)
  ✅ Ephemeral data (doesn't need to persist after session ends)
  ✅ Client-to-client messaging (one user to others)
  ✅ Lower DB overhead (no WAL/replication slot)
  ✅ Custom events with arbitrary payload

Use POSTGRES CHANGES when:
  ✅ You want DB row data synced to connected clients automatically
  ✅ Multiple clients need to bootstrap state from DB + get live updates
  ✅ Data MUST persist regardless of client connection
  ✅ Offline clients catch up by querying DB on reconnect
  ❌ NOT for high-frequency updates (each change = DB write + WAL + broadcast)
  ❌ NOT for cursor/presence (use Broadcast instead)
  ❌ NOT for tables with >10 writes/sec (use broadcast_changes trigger instead)

Use BROADCAST_CHANGES TRIGGER when:
  ✅ You have high-write tables that need realtime but Postgres Changes is too heavy
  ✅ You want DB change broadcast without WAL replication overhead
  ✅ Best of both: persists in DB + lightweight realtime notification
```
